(3) In the third stage of the argument (§ 39 ff.)‚ the whole subject οἱ agriculture, upon which he enlarges at great length, would fall away, and with it the special pertinency of not a few of his illustrations. It is true that Varro was an expert in this direction,'but his work on agriculture was· not yet written, while Cato’s book on the same subject was a classic. (4) In the more technical arguments with which the fourth objection to old age is met (§ 66 ff.)‚ there is nothing so personal to Cato that an adequate substitute might not have been found, if the discourse had been put in the mouth of another. And yet here, as in the intro- ductory sections, and throughout the dialogue, while the personal allusions or recollections may be no better for the purposes of the essay than similar personalities connected with another speaker, the total effect of them all could not possibly be produced apart from the heroic figure of Cato.¹ The choice was in fact inevitable, and the brief dialogue in which the old censor, the hater of all things Greek, is made to stand as sponsor for the wisdom born to Cicero out of Greek philosophy, is in no other direction so fruit-
